**W1-D1-Classes_and_Objects**

**What is a Class and Object?**
Class = blueprint. Object = real thing built from that blueprint.
Example: `Car` is the blueprint. `car1 = Car(...)` is one real car built from it.
You can create many objects from one class — each holds its own separate data.

---

**1. Car**

```python
class Car:  # creating a blueprint called Car
    
    def __init__(self, brand, model, year):  
        # __init__ runs automatically the moment you create an object
        # self = this specific object (car1 or car2, whoever is being created)
        self.brand = brand  # permanently save brand on this object
        self.model = model  # permanently save model on this object
        self.year = year    # permanently save year on this object
        # without self.x = x, the value is lost after __init__ finishes

    def display_info(self):  
        # method = function that belongs to this class
        # self gives access to this object's own saved data
        print(f"{self.year} {self.brand} {self.model}")

    def is_new(self):
        return self.year >= 2023  
        # return sends value back to whoever called it
        # True if year is 2023 or above, False if not

car1 = Car("Toyota", "Corolla", 2022)  
# creates object, automatically runs __init__, saves brand/model/year on car1

car2 = Car("Honda", "Civic", 2023)    
# completely separate object, changing car1 never affects car2

car1.display_info()  # prints: 2022 Toyota Corolla
car2.display_info()  # prints: 2023 Honda Civic
print(car1.is_new()) # False — 2022 is not >= 2023
print(car2.is_new()) # True — 2023 is >= 2023
```

